'''Perfecto "Jun" Rivas Yasay Jr.''' (born January 27, 1947) is a [[Philippine nationality law|Filipino]] formerly-[[United States nationality law|American]] [[bureaucrat]] who served as [[Secretary of Foreign Affairs (Philippines)|Secretary of Foreign Affairs]] of the [[Philippines]] in an ''[[ad interim]]'' basis from June 30, 2016 until March 8, 2017, the rejection of his appointment by the [[Commission on Appointments]] over eligibility concerns resulting from questions on his citizenship.

He served as former chairman of the [[Securities and Exchange Commission (Philippines)|Securities and Exchange Commission]] (SEC) and was [[Bangon Pilipinas]] Party's vice-presidential candidate in the [[Philippine general election, 2010|2010 Philippine elections]], running alongside [[Eddie Villanueva]].{{citation needed|date=March 2017}}

==Early life and education==
Yasay was born on January 27, 1947 to Perfecto Yasay Sr., a pastor, and Deborah Rivas, a public school teacher, in [[Kidapawan]], [[North Cotabato]]. He finished his secondary education at Davao City High School in 1963 and received his Bachelor of Arts in political science at [[Central Philippine University]], [[Iloilo City]] in 1967. He earned his law degree at the [[University of the Philippines]] and has MBA units in business studies from [[Ateneo de Manila University]].{{citation needed|date=March 2017}}

==Career==
===Legal work===
Yasay became a member of the Bar of the United States Supreme Court, and the U.S. Circuit Court of Appeals. Civil, criminal, and administrative litigation, public advocacy, corporation law, and election law are among his areas of expertise.{{citation needed|date=March 2017}} While in New York, he was managing director of the Maceda Philippine News from 1983 to 1987 and senior partner at two law firms—Maceda, Yasay & Tolentino, Esqs., and Yasay & De Castro, Esqs.—from 1979 to 1990.{{citation needed|date=March 2017}} In the Philippines, he was commissioner of San Jose, Yasay & Santos Law Offices from 1987 to 1993.{{citation needed|date=March 2017}} Yasay is also an incorporator of Jacinto Finance, Marilene J. Group Corp., and Cricem Inc. He is also a stockholder of M and F Stores Inc.{{citation needed|date=March 2017}}

===SEC Chairman===
In 1993, he was assigned as associate commissioner of SEC. He was chairman from 1995 to 2000.{{citation needed|date=March 2017}}

====Estrada impeachment trial====
Yasay was among those who testified in the impeachment trial against President [[Joseph Estrada]] on charges of corruption. The probe led to the ouster of Estrada, known as [[People Power II|EDSA People Power II]] in 2001.{{citation needed|date=March 2017}}

On February 15, 2010, Yasay apologized to Estrada for "hurting and offending him" but clarified that this was not a retraction of his testimony on the deposed president's "abuse of authority and corruption."{{citation needed|date=March 2017}}

===2010 vice presidential bid===
On November 29, 2009, he accepted the nomination of the [[Bangon Pilipinas Party]] to be its candidate for vice president as the running mate of [[Jesus is Lord Church]] founder and president [[Eddie Villanueva]]. In a statement, he said that he has also been offered a slot in the senatorial slate of three other political parties.{{citation needed|date=March 2017}} Among his campaign platform points, Yasay conveyed that the practice of using big-name endorsers should be stopped because it makes the elections a matter of money and popularity. He also said that the voters' will only base their votes via the endorsers of the candidate, and that the biggest setback in the fight against corruption was the quick pardon of [[Joseph Estrada]].{{citation needed|date=March 2017}} Yasay lost to [[Makati]] City Mayor [[Jejomar Binay]] in the [[Philippine general election, 2010|vice-presidential elections]].{{citation needed|date=March 2017}}

===Secretary of Foreign Affairs===
[[File:Philippines Foreign Secretary Yasay Addresses Reporters at a News Conference (28502879381).jpg|thumb|left|250px|Yasay with U.S. Secretary of State [[John Kerry]] during their bilateral meeting on July 27, 2016]]
He accepted the offer of [[President of the Philippines|President]] [[Rodrigo Duterte]] to join his Cabinet on May 18, 2016.<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.rappler.com/nation/133471-yasay-accepts-duterte-offer-acting-dfa|title=Yasay accepts Duterte offer to be acting DFA chief|website=Rappler|access-date=May 30, 2016}}</ref> During his tenure he represented the Duterte administration's policy of an "independent foreign policy" distancing the Philippines from the United States. According to Yasay, the United States has used a "[[carrot and stick]]" foreign policy in regards to the Philippines since for their own interest to the detriment of the latter.<ref name="usfail">{{cite news|last1=Palumbarit|first1=Veronica|title=Yasay on PHL's shift in foreign policy: 'America has failed us'|url=http://www.gmanetwork.com/news/story/584026/news/nation/yasay-on-phl-s-shift-in-foreign-policy-america-has-failed-us|accessdate=9 March 2017|work=GMA News|date=6 October 2016}}</ref> Yasay was meant by Duterte to serve the post until mid-2017, when Duterte plans to appoint his running mate, Senator [[Alan Peter Cayetano]], as his successor.<ref>{{cite news|title=Alan Peter to replace Yasay in DFA|url=http://www.philstar.com/headlines/2016/12/30/1658064/alan-peter-replace-yasay-dfa|accessdate=9 March 2017|publisher=The Philippine Star|date=30 December 2016}}</ref> On March 8, 2017, however, Yasay's appointment was rejected by a unanimous vote of 15-0 by the [[Commission on Appointments]] due to questions about his [[Philippine nationality law|Philippine citizenship]] status after a period of [[Citizenship of the United States|United States citizenship]].<ref>{{cite news|last1=Fernandez|first1=Butch|title=CA rejects Yasay, defers Lopez's confirmation|url=http://www.businessmirror.com.ph/ca-rejects-yasay-defers-lopezs-confirmation/|accessdate=9 March 2017|work=Business Mirror|date=8 March 2017}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|last=Ager|first=Maila|title=CA rejects appointment of Yasay|date=March 8, 2017|newspaper=[[Philippine Daily Inquirer]]|url=http://newsinfo.inquirer.net/878680/ca-rejects-appointment-of-yasay|accessdate=2017-03-08}}</ref>

==Board memberships and philanthropy==
He is past chairman of  the Board of Trustees of Central Philippine University.{{citation needed|date=March 2017}}

==Personal life==
He is married to former Population Commission executive director Cecile Joaquin and has three children, all [[Americans|United States citizens]]. He used to have [[United States nationality law|American citizenship]] until 2016 but has yet to retake the [[Philippine nationality law|Philippine oath of citizenship]]; there is debate whether he is now [[statelessness|stateless]] or not.<ref>{{cite news |title="Yasay: American, Filipino or stateless?"|date=2017|url=http://globalnation.inquirer.net/152893/yasay-american-filipino-stateless|publisher=''[[Philippine Daily Inquirer]]''|access-date=February 26, 2017}}</ref>

